text.i: Traffic Study – The Lakes of Argyle, Argyle, TX

page.text: Lee Engineering has completed the traffic analysis of the proposed Lakes of Argyle residential
development located on the west side of US 377 between Harpole Road and Old Justin Road in
The Lakes of Argyle development is proposed to be located on the west side of US 377 between
Harpole Road and Old Justin Road in Argyle, Texas. The site is currently undeveloped.
Figure 1 provides an aerial view of the location. The Lakes of Argyle development is proposed
as a 168-unit single family residential development, with access provided via one full-access
driveway on Harpole Road and one full-access driveway on Old Justin Road, and was assumed
to be complete in 2014. The proposed site plan is provided in Figure 2.
US 377 is a two-lane undivided roadway with a posted speed limit of 50 miles per hour (mph)
and approximate 10-foot shoulders. US 377 is classified as a Type A Major Arterial (six lanes
divided) in the Town of Argyle Thoroughfare Plan amended in April of 2010. Railroad tracks
run parallel to US 377 on the west side.
Harpole Road is a two-lane undivided roadway with a posted speed limit of 30 mph. Harpole
Road is classified as a Type E Rural Collector (two lanes undivided) in the Town of Argyle
Thoroughfare Plan west of US 377. East of US 377, Harpole Road is classified as a Type D
Minor Collector (two lanes undivided). One full-access site driveway will be located along
Harpole Road. The intersection of Harpole Road and US 377 is currently signalized.
Old Justin Road is a two-lane undivided roadway with a posted speed limit of 30 mph. Old
Justin Road is classified as a Type E Rural Collector (two lanes undivided) in the Town of
Argyle Thoroughfare Plan. One full-access site driveway will be located along Old Justin Road.
The intersection of Old Justin Road and US 377 is stop-controlled along Old Justin Road.
The existing intersection lane configurations are shown in Figure 3, along with the proposed
driveway locations for the Lakes of Argyle development.

text.i: Operational Analysis of Study Area Intersections

page.text: The Level of Service (LOS) of an intersection is a qualitative measure of capacity and operating
conditions that is directly related to vehicle delay. The LOS criteria for a signalized intersection
are shown in Table 2. LOS is given a letter designation from A to F, with LOS A representing
very short delays (less than 10 seconds of average control delay per vehicle) and LOS F
representing very long delays (more than 80 seconds of average control delay per vehicle). As a
practical consideration, LOS D, ranging from 35.1 to 55 seconds of average control delay per
vehicle, is typically considered the limit of acceptable operation.

For unsignalized intersections, the levels of service as shown in Table 3 are defined by average
control delay in seconds per vehicle. Additional performance measures such as volume to
capacity (v/c) ratios and queue lengths also provide an indication of operations. For example, at
two-way stop controlled intersections, main street traffic volumes may impose longer average
delays for a small number of side-street vehicles, thus creating vehicle delays which correspond
to a poor level of service. Motorists and agencies will typically accept longer delays (LOS E
to F) if gaps in the traffic stream are anticipated within a reasonable timeframe and the side street
traffic volumes do not warrant a traffic signal. As a general guide, gap acceptance thresholds for
the longer delay values can be defined when the v/c ratios are under 0.85, which corresponds to
85 percent capacity usage for that movement. Therefore, a traffic movement with a poor level of
service and a v/c value under 0.85 could be considered as operating acceptably.

page.text: As shown in Table 7, Harpole Road and Old Justin Road currently operate at acceptable levels of

operating at acceptable levels of service with the addition of site traffic.
The proposed main site roadway for the Lakes of Argyle development was analyzed to determine
if right turn deceleration lanes would be required. Based on guidelines presented in TxDOT’s
Access Management Manual and used by several cities in the Dallas-Fort Worth area, right turn
deceleration lanes are typically considered under the following conditions:
 Right turn volumes greater than 50 vph (if posted speed limit greater than 45 mph)
 Right turn volumes greater than 60 vph (if posted speed limit less than/equal to 45 mph)
Table 8 summarizes the predicted right turn volumes under total traffic conditions.

text.b: Table 8: Right Turn Deceleration Lane Analysis Results

page.text: Based on the projected traffic volumes in Table 8, a right turn deceleration lane is not required at
the intersection of the main site roadway with either Harpole Road or Old Justin Road.

page.text: Based on the results presented in Table 10, the projected traffic volumes under total traffic
conditions do not exceed the left turn lane guidelines for a design speed of 40 mph, and would
therefore not exceed the volume thresholds for a 30 mph speed limit. Thus, installation of an
eastbound left turn lane on Harpole Road or a westbound left turn lane on Old Justin Road is not
required at the site driveway locations.
As part of this traffic analysis, the available and required intersection sight distances for
motorists accessing the adjacent roadways from the proposed site access driveways were
analyzed. The sight distance required at the proposed site driveways was estimated using the
procedures developed by the American Association of State Highway and Transportation
Officials (AASHTO) and published in the 2011 edition of A Policy on Geometric Design of
Highways and Streets. At these locations, the motorist should be able to see if and when
adequate gaps exist to perform their desired maneuver. Table 11 presents the required and
available sight distance for vehicles exiting the proposed site driveway.

Sight distance is anticipated to increase with removal of trees located on property.
Comparing the field investigation results of the available sight distance to the required sight
distance indicates that adequate sight distance is provided for passenger cars along Harpole Road
and along Old Justin Road at the main site roadway.
